english:
  title: A Farewell Poem for Official An Gyeongjae Upon His Appointment as Governor of Sangju
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the southeastern provinces and prefectures, Gyeongju stands foremost, with Sangju close behind. This is why the region bears the name Gyeongsang. Yet those bearing the emperor's mandate must first pass through Sangju before reaching Gyeongju. Thus the currents of civilization flow southward from Sangju, never flowing northward from Gyeongju.

    In the spring of the third year of Zhizheng, Official An Gyeongjae departed his post as Censor and Scholar of the Right Library to assume the governorship of Sangju. The worthy gentlemen and fine companions gathered to offer their congratulations, saying: "The official is stern within yet harmonious without, spare in speech yet swift in action. His sternness and brevity inspire respect and obedience; his harmony and swiftness win hearts and followers. Those bearing the emperor's mandate, who once merely admired his name, now witness his virtue. Though there be tigers fierce as Ning Cheng and hawks keen as Zhi Du, surely his integrity will temper their cruelty, and even those scheming like Sang Yang will restrain their harshness. The people of Sangju shall surely find respite!"

    Since the winds of civilization flow southward from Sangju, not only Sangju alone receives this blessing—all of Gyeongsang Province shares in it.

    Yet I say to these gentlemen: You know one truth but not the other. Wealth and advancement are what all men desire. But to receive deep trust from one's sovereign, to bear weighty expectations from one's people, and yet to remain humbly steadfast in the rushing stream—such men are scarce as one in a thousand. The world thinks nothing strange when men with aging parents at home, with younger siblings to support, abandon their duties to chase a day's glory in high office. But our Official An achieved highest honors in the imperial examinations, his writings shine brightest in our Eastern land, he has graced the finest posts and wielded power at court. Last year he took his family homeward to serve his mother, yet before his journey was half complete, the emperor's summons recalled him to wield the authority of the censorate. The sovereign's trust in him runs deep, and the people's expectations weigh heavily upon him.

    Yet he seeks assignment to distant lands, that he might better care for his aging mother, and arranges for his brothers to serve in offices both near and far. His integrity and humble restraint, his filial piety and brotherly devotion—these shall inspire the present age and endure for generations. Can his influence be confined to one province, his virtue to one region alone? As the sovereign's trust deepens and the people's hopes grow weightier, his ascent from the Silver Gate to the Golden Hall, continuing the legacy of Kim Jin-suk, is something we may well anticipate with confidence.

    The gentlemen all agreed, and thus I have recorded this.
  footnotes:
    - The 'tiger of Ning Cheng' and 'hawk of Zhi Du' refer to famous ruthless administrators of ancient China—metaphors for harsh governance that Official An's virtue might temper.
    - The 'scheme of Sang Yang' alludes to exploitative fiscal policies; a contrast to virtuous administration.
    - Kim Jin-suk (金眞肅) was a renowned minister of an earlier era, serving as a model of exemplary official conduct.
    - The 'Silver Gate' (鈴閣) and 'Golden Hall' (黃閣) represent the progression from lower to increasingly senior positions at court.
